<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Housing Standards Review Inquiry response from the Micropower Council</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Micropower</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Council</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the Environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Audit Committee’s decision to launch this inquiry at such an important point in the development of regulations for the new build sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Housing Standards Review proposal to repeal the Planning and Energy Act will remove the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only policy tool explicitly incentivising on-site renewables in new homes. This tool must remain available to local authorities at least until Building Regulations are sufficiently strong to drive uptake of on-site low carbon and renewable energy production in new homes. In addition, the Code for Sustainable Ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mes should also remain available until Building Regulations are strengthened.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that the level set for Part L Building Regulations of just 6% CO2 reduction for new homes does not set an ambitious enough target and drive the market in this sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> enough evidence has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been explored about the cost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">building new energy efficient homes and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fact that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cost to retrofit homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to a higher efficiency standard is greater than at new build. A higher standard of energy efficient new build is cheaper for the economy overall than building lower cost housing because of the overall energy savings achieved, locked in for the lifetime of the building.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">About the Micropower Council</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Micropower Council represents companies and organisations active in the micro-generation sector and campaigns on behalf of its members for a genuine mass market for small scale, low and zero carbon electricity and heat generating technologies. Micropower Council members include manufacturers and installers of microgeneration technologies as well as energy suppliers and other trade associations active in the sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">For more information on any of the responses in this document or on the Micropower Council, please contact Anna Livesey: anna.livesey@micropower.co.uk. </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Response</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a decision was announced to adopt only a 6% reduction in CO2 emissions compared to the 2010 standard under Part L Building Regulations, rather than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">halfway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to zero carbons target. This approach is not ambitious enough </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and does </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not impose strict enough carbon reduction targets to incentivise the integration of on-site renewables (such as solar energy systems, heat pumps and biomass boilers) into new properties.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a result of this decision, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Plannin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g and Energy Act's ‘Merton Rule’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is the only policy tool explicitly incentivising on-site renewables in new home</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s. It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must remain available to local authorities at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">least until Building Regulations are sufficiently strong to drive uptake of on-site low carbon and renewable energy production in new homes (which will not be befor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e 2016 at the earliest). It is also still</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> important </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> driv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> higher energy efficiency standards as well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as low carbon and renewable technologies in non-residential buildings, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some of this is already incentivised through FITs and the RHI.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One of the main issues is that e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nergy efficiency measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and on-site renewables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are more cost effective to install at construction than retrofit and not driving uptake in new homes will create a legacy of buildings that need to be brought up to standard. Initiatives such as the Green Deal will need to find budget to deal with this legacy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Building of new homes is seen as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tant to improve the economy. However, building more homes to a higher energy efficiency standard makes more sense economically. The lower running costs of these buildings and therefore savings to consumers will be locked-in creating an overall net benefit. A benefit that outweighs costs and is cheaper than paying to achieve carbon reduction and renewables targets through bills or taxation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Merton Borough Council (on whose initiative the Planning and Energy Act was based) estimate that if applied nationally the Act could save 160,000 tonnes of CO2 annually and contribute to an annual total renewable energy infrastructure industry of £1,125,000,000. Figures that should not be overlooked when considering the repeal of this important Act.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes also provides a set of graduated standards for energy and environmental performance that exceed the minimum levels in Building Regulations.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Decision making process</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have heard anecdotal evidence that the decision making process regarding the repeal of the Act was not robust. A Communities and Local Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">task group was set up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">representatives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from across industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to develop the proposals for the Housing Standards Review. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The group met three times</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and at the final meeting in February 2013 the group was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unable to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reach any meaningful conclusions. Therefore not all members of this group were supportive of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> final proposal to abol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ish the Planning and Energy Act and consideration was not taken for the views of all those involved in the group. </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br /><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Impact on existing commitments </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this year’s budget t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chancellor reaffirmed the Government commitment to Zero Carbon Homes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government has made other legally binding commitments on CO2 reduction and Renewable Energy Production. In February 2013, the Prime Minister launched DECC’s Energy Efficiency Mission and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emphasised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">importance of green energy for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">climate change, the economy and business.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not reflected </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the current Part L standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the proposal to repeal the Planning and Energy Act.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There will be an immediate impact for many Local Authorities if the act is repealed. For example, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he use of the Planning and Energy Act appears in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> London Plan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that all new major residential developments should set energy efficiency standa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rds above current requirements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and include on-site generation. As a result, 63% of new dwellings in London will have a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10% renewable energy in 2014–16, this achievement will be jeopardised of the Act is repealed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Part L in detail</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more ambitious target </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for new build under Part L of the building regulations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would support industry to develop its supply chain thus driving down costs and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">encouraging more retrofit installations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in existing buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, because this supply will now take longer to develop, costs will remain higher for longer and as a result consumers are less likely to install retrofit installations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst consumers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in new build homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will benefit from some reduction in their energy bills, up to £200 according to DCLG, the more ambitious target would have created savings up to five times higher. Thus fewer consumers will be protected from rising fuel costs and volatility in pricing. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regulatory burden known as the ‘one in two out’ rule has created a distortion in how the costs and benefits are compared and the resulting savings to the economy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the level of the economy overall the extra costs of the higher target</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are more than funded by the additional savings and this has not been taken into consideration when creating the regulations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Using data in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2012 consultation Impact Assessment the cost to society of the ‘halfway’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach was estimated at £317m. However, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> analysis did not include the benefits to consumers (£375m). When these figures are included </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in a cost benefit analysis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is a net benefit to society of £58m. An analysis of the final Impact Assessment suggests the net benefit is even greater; the cost to society is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as £311m but the benefits to consumers are £391m giving a net benefit to society of £81m. Furthermore, using 2014 cost assumptions (when the regulations come into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forces) the cost to society is estimated as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">£272m giving a net benefit of over £100m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (see appendix A)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">osts of creating energy efficient homes are simply being displaced to the future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at greater cost to consumers and the economy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and furthermore the costs of retrofit installation will be greater than at new build. Incentives such as the Green Deal and the Renewable Heat Incentive will be required to find additional budget to deal with this legacy cost.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Wider housing issues</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is recognised that there is a need in the UK to build more new homes and more affordable new homes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We understand there is an argument that in order to ‘kick start’ this market, increased development costs should be avoided.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the result of this approach is to not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accommodate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> building</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more energy efficient homes. This creates legacy costs for Government, dealing with these inefficient homes at a later date. And for consumers, who will be locked into higher energy costs until such time as retrofit improvements can be made, driving more households into fuel poverty.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here is evidence available that new homes built to higher energy efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> standards do have an increased value. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A DECC report published in June 2013, ‘An investigation of the effect of EPC ratings on house prices’, found that: ‘there is a positive relationship between energy rating and dwelling price per square metre. Compared to dwellings rated EPC band G, dwellings with higher EPC ratings have sold at a statistically significant price premium and the pattern of the resul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts is consistent and plausible.’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is also evidence that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new energy efficient </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">homes can be built at low cost and affordable prices. Richard Rogers’ Home Shell, was developed in response to the then Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott’s Design for Manufacture challenge to create a house that could be built </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from modern materials for £60,000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The building is designed to be energy efficient and a development of such homes has been in existence since 2007.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Conclusions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Part L Building Regulations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">set at just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 6% CO2 reduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, announced in July </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for new homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not set an ambitious enough target </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> drive the market in this sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The costs of building new energy efficient homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with on-site renewables </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is cheaper for the economy overall than building lower cost housing because of the overall energy savings achieved, locked in for the lifetime of the building. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The lower running costs of energy efficient buildings and therefore savings to consumers create an overall net benefit that outweighs costs and is cheaper than paying to achieve carbon reduction and renewables targets through bills or taxation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore the cost to retrofit homes to a higher efficiency standard is greater than at new build.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Therefore the Planning and Energy Act must remain available to local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to enable them to drive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uptake of on-site low carbon and renewable energy production in new homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at least until </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tighter standards exist in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Building Regulations.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In addition, the Code for Sustainable Homes should also remain available until such time as the Building Regulations are strengthened. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix A</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Part L Building Regulations: Cost Benefit Analysis</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Bui</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lding Regulations model uses the Zero Carbon Homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> energy profile for different house types to estimate the cost and</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> benefits of installing microgeneration </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technologies (PV taken as a proxy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and energy efficiency measures in new buildings.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Using data from the 2012 consultation and Parsons Brinkerhoff* solar PV costs, the cost to society of the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">halfway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ approach was estimated at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£317m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The analysis also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimated that the policy would result in benefits to consumers of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£375m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Therefore a cost benefit analysis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> suggest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that there would be a net benefit to society of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£58m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the latest analysis the benefits to consumers has increased to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£391m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">due to some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changes in the dwelling numbers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and to a small increase in both gas and electricity emission factor. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The analysis is based on the Green Book 3.5% SDR. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="293" height="187" alt="image004" /><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="292" height="188" alt="image006" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£311m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is the cost of installing PV systems in new buildings using Parsons Brinckerhoff 2012 estimates (in line with DCLG September 2013 IA).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£272m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would be the cost of installing PVs if Parsons Brinckerhoff 2014 cost estimates were input in the model.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£391m </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is the household savings using DCLG September 2013 revised dwelling assumptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£119m </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is the net benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£81m </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">using the 2012 figures)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">*Parsons Brinkerhoff, Solar PV Cost Update (May 2012) </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:20pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:20pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>